task apps.

00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:50.700
IAN NI-LEWIS: You know what?

00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:51.820
I don't call them anything.

00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:52.470
RETO MEIER: Maybe that's
the problem.

00:04:52.470 --> 00:04:53.040
You call them task apps and--

00:04:53.040 --> 00:04:55.480
IAN NI-LEWIS: Maybe
they're auto apps.

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:58.590
The thing about device profile
is, I think the terminology

00:04:58.590 --> 00:05:01.480
comes from the idea of having
a device in a completely

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:04.050
different state for
certain things.

00:05:04.050 --> 00:05:07.610
And we certainly introduced that
concept when we started

00:05:07.610 --> 00:05:08.920
looking into Docs.

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:11.700
And the idea is you have one
profile when you're undocked

00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:13.890
versus another profile
while you're docked.

00:05:13.890 --> 00:05:15.810
But these apps that we're
looking at today

00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:17.470
go far beyond that.

00:05:17.470 --> 00:05:20.470
And I think it's almost hard
to talk about a specific

00:05:20.470 --> 00:05:24.160
profile because there are
multiple overlapping things

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:25.530
that each app can do.

00:05:25.530 --> 00:05:26.130
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:29.250
IAN NI-LEWIS: But the core of
it is we're going to change

00:05:29.250 --> 00:05:32.740
something in the system, or
possibly just do something in

00:05:32.740 --> 00:05:35.870
this system when you execute an
action, when the conditions

00:05:35.870 --> 00:05:37.030
of the system change.

00:05:37.030 --> 00:05:37.460
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:05:37.460 --> 00:05:40.320
And so the idea here is that
rather than having a single

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:44.570
toggle, you're able to say I'm
at home, I'm at work, I am

00:05:44.570 --> 00:05:49.060
entering a meeting, whatever
your profile case is.

00:05:49.060 --> 00:05:51.470
And execute a whole bunch of
different settings changes or

00:05:51.470 --> 00:05:54.760
launch a bunch of apps, and as
Ian says, basically perform a

00:05:54.760 --> 00:05:59.220
series of actions in relation to
that change in environment.

00:05:59.220 --> 00:06:01.290
So they can all change the
volume in ring tones, they can

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:03.230
all change brightness, they
can all modify your

00:06:03.230 --> 00:06:05.290
connectivity settings as well.

00:06:05.290 --> 00:06:07.610
Some of the apps, I think Tasker
in particular, goes

00:06:07.610 --> 00:06:09.400
significantly further
than that.

00:06:09.400 --> 00:06:12.460
But these are the core things
that I think anyone

00:06:12.460 --> 00:06:14.310
downloading one of these
apps is going to want

00:06:14.310 --> 00:06:15.610
to be able to do.

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:18.400
Mute the volume, change your
ring tone, alter the screen

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:21.210
brightness based on time
of day or location.

00:06:21.210 --> 00:06:24.460
IAN NI-LEWIS: And in addition
to that, although it doesn't

00:06:24.460 --> 00:06:28.170
really fit into the profile
idea, I think I would add

00:06:28.170 --> 00:06:31.870
sending alerts and
notifications,

00:06:31.870 --> 00:06:33.470
SMSes, things like that.

00:06:33.470 --> 00:06:35.240
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:35.500
OK.

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:37.130
So these three apps.

00:06:37.130 --> 00:06:39.030
Like we said, they have these
things in common.

00:06:39.030 --> 00:06:42.300
I like to think of them as three
variations on a theme.

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:44.070
And we're going to see this
as we go through.

00:06:44.070 --> 00:06:47.070
Tasker is kind of like
a self driving car.

00:06:47.070 --> 00:06:48.925
You spend a lot of time
setting it up.

00:06:48.925 --> 00:06:51.360
And once it's going, you just
sit there and it does

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:52.560
everything for you.

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:55.250
IAN NI-LEWIS: I wonder if that's
a really good analogy

00:06:55.250 --> 00:06:56.280
or if it's going to resonate.

00:06:56.280 --> 00:06:59.190
Because while everyone can
understand the experience of

00:06:59.190 --> 00:07:00.520
getting in a self-driving
car--

00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:03.020
I mean, everyone's been
driven by someone--

00:07:03.020 --> 00:07:05.340
only people like you and I know
what it takes to set up a

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:06.510
self-driving car.

00:07:06.510 --> 00:07:07.270
RETO MEIER: This is very true.

00:07:07.270 --> 00:07:08.160
IAN NI-LEWIS: Hours
in the morning.

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:08.580
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:07:08.580 --> 00:07:09.580
I know, right?

00:07:09.580 --> 00:07:11.380
You've got to plug things in.

00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:12.300
We shouldn't go into.

00:07:12.300 --> 00:07:12.670
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:07:12.670 --> 00:07:14.580
RETO MEIER: NSC Task
Launcher is kind of

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:15.930
like driving an auto.

00:07:15.930 --> 00:07:19.210
It does most of the hard work
for you, but you still need to

00:07:19.210 --> 00:07:20.080
initiate the action.

00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:21.280
You still need to
do something.

00:07:21.280 --> 00:07:23.600
And you still have some
element of control.

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:25.900
Profile Widget goes
the other way.

00:07:25.900 --> 00:07:28.650
You basically have to initiate
it yourself entirely, choose

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:32.260
which widget to click, which
profile you want to switch to.

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:34.620
So you have to be conscious of
that rather than just being

00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:37.570
able to use a particular
location.

00:07:37.570 --> 00:07:40.450
So let's talk a little
bit about what we

00:07:40.450 --> 00:07:41.110
want from the apps.

00:07:41.110 --> 00:07:43.820
So we've talked about what they
can do, what they all

00:07:43.820 --> 00:07:47.440
should do, and how they vary
at a very high level.

00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:49.820
So what are the things that you
want to see in an app like

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:51.120
this for it to be your go-to?

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:52.340
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, I think the
most important thing that

00:07:52.340 --> 00:07:54.750
I want is for it to be able
to control everything.

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:57.090
I don't want any part of
my system to remain

00:07:57.090 --> 00:07:58.800
untouched by this app.

00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:02.130
Now, of course, as we talked
about yesterday-- we had a

00:08:02.130 --> 00:08:04.850
long conversation about
permissions and how wanting to

00:08:04.850 --> 00:08:08.090
control everything imposes
some really interesting

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:11.630
restrictions and
responsibilities on the

00:08:11.630 --> 00:08:12.810
developer of the app.

00:08:12.810 --> 00:08:13.990
But I want it to
do everything.

00:08:13.990 --> 00:08:16.320
I don't want there to be
anything that I can do to the

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:19.810
phone that this app can't,
because I want it to be an

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:22.420
agent or a proxy for me.

00:08:22.420 --> 00:08:27.920
I also want to make sure that it
can combine multiple events

00:08:27.920 --> 00:08:32.530
and multiple actions with
multiple conditions, because

00:08:32.530 --> 00:08:35.990
the sort of profile that I can
use to tell you that I'm at

00:08:35.990 --> 00:08:40.250
work, for instance, unless
it's got machine learning

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:43.289
along the lines of
Google Now--

00:08:43.289 --> 00:08:45.900
only next year's version
of Google Now--

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:47.730
it probably doesn't know
that I'm at work.

00:08:47.730 --> 00:08:49.410
It probably doesn't know
that I'm in a meeting.

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:52.910
I need to be able to tell it
that, yeah, when I'm attached

00:08:52.910 --> 00:08:57.560
to this Wi-Fi network during
these hours of the day, and

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:00.170
possibly some other conditions,
that's when I need

00:09:00.170 --> 00:09:01.730
to be not disturbed.

00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:04.710
Or that's when I can accept
text messages.

00:09:04.710 --> 00:09:07.470
So I need to be able
to push all of

00:09:07.470 --> 00:09:08.920
those into one container.

00:09:08.920 --> 00:09:12.080
And several of the apps that
we looked at have this

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:14.750
functionality, but only
in the pro version.

00:09:14.750 --> 00:09:16.233
So that's something
to look for.

00:09:16.233 --> 00:09:16.980
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:09:16.980 --> 00:09:19.620
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now the other
thing that you need, I think

00:09:19.620 --> 00:09:21.400
you mentioned, is these
things are really

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:22.330
difficult to set up.

00:09:22.330 --> 00:09:23.260
RETO MEIER: Yes, they are.

00:09:23.260 --> 00:09:26.520
And I think the core thing here
is that it's something

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:29.090
which if you describe the
functionality to people, it's

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:29.640
kind of obvious.

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:32.920
And there's been things like
this built into mobile phone

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:35.230
operating systems for a
long time on and off.

00:09:35.230 --> 00:09:38.440
This notion of being able to
click a button, change a

00:09:38.440 --> 00:09:41.710
setting, and you're at home, at
work, receiving calls, not

00:09:41.710 --> 00:09:42.470
receiving calls.

00:09:42.470 --> 00:09:45.030
I think the challenge has always
been presenting this in

00:09:45.030 --> 00:09:47.860
a way that just regular
people can use.

00:09:47.860 --> 00:09:48.850
At the moment--

00:09:48.850 --> 00:09:51.690
and we'll see it varies for
each of these apps.

00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:54.140
But at the moment, you've got
that tendency to feel like

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:55.920
you're having to program
the phone, right?

00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:57.150
And that's what you want
to get away from.

00:09:57.150 --> 00:09:59.850
So when we say easy to use,
what we mean is easy to

00:09:59.850 --> 00:10:02.110
configure, especially.

00:10:02.110 --> 00:10:04.200
The actual use case, I think,
for all three is pretty

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:04.930
straightforward.

00:10:04.930 --> 00:10:06.940
But the configuration
is the trick.

00:10:06.940 --> 00:10:09.350
And so we really want to make
it as easy as possible.

00:10:09.350 --> 00:10:12.500
And that kind of relates
to the last point.

00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:14.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah there's
really two ways that you can

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:16.600
make this easy to use.

00:10:16.600 --> 00:10:21.110
You can either make it very easy
to program, which if you

00:10:21.110 --> 00:10:24.330
figure out how to do
that, let me know.

00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:25.580
RETO MEIER: Yeah, that
could be [INAUDIBLE].

00:10:28.260 --> 00:10:29.830
IAN NI-LEWIS: I used to program
games, and one of the

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:34.890
things that we would always say
is, boy, I don't want to

00:10:34.890 --> 00:10:35.790
program all this game play.

00:10:35.790 --> 00:10:37.970
It seems like the designers
should be able to do that.

00:10:37.970 --> 00:10:41.380
And so multiple projects,
this happened to me.

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:42.900
I wasn't always the one
calling the shots.

00:10:42.900 --> 00:10:46.780
But you make a scripting
language and give it to the

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:49.450
designers, and they're
like, oh thanks.

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:50.830
And then they come to you
and say, hey, can

00:10:50.830 --> 00:10:53.720
you write this script?

00:10:53.720 --> 00:10:56.530
And you realize, wow, I just
spent a huge amount of time

00:10:56.530 --> 00:10:59.090
making this scriptable, and I'm
going to have to write all

00:10:59.090 --> 00:11:00.800
the code to script it.

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:03.330
And that's the feeling that
I get with these apps.

00:11:03.330 --> 00:11:05.590
For a software engineer or
someone who's used to thinking

00:11:05.590 --> 00:11:08.570
in terms of code, these
are very easy to use.

00:11:08.570 --> 00:11:10.460
Some of them are more cumbersome
than others,

00:11:10.460 --> 00:11:11.390
navigation-wise.

00:11:11.390 --> 00:11:12.850
Some of them are prettier
than others.

00:11:12.850 --> 00:11:14.780
But the concepts are easy.

00:11:14.780 --> 00:11:16.560
At the same time, for most
people, I think it's going to

00:11:16.560 --> 00:11:21.150
be like programming a VCR, which
is, you want to do it.

00:11:21.150 --> 00:11:21.770
You know what you want.

00:11:21.770 --> 00:11:24.520
But you're never
going to do it.

00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:26.300
You're never going to figure
that out, right?

00:11:26.300 --> 00:11:28.067
RETO MEIER: It'll one person
in the house who figures it

00:11:28.067 --> 00:11:28.810
out, and that's it.

00:11:28.810 --> 00:11:29.250
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:11:29.250 --> 00:11:30.110
RETO MEIER: They're the go-to.

00:11:30.110 --> 00:11:30.350
Can you set up the--

00:11:30.350 --> 00:11:32.520
IAN NI-LEWIS: No, one person
in the extended family, and

00:11:32.520 --> 00:11:33.760
you don't want to be that guy.

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:34.815
RETO MEIER: You do not
want to be that guy.

00:11:34.815 --> 00:11:37.650
IAN NI-LEWIS: So let's take
a tip from the VCR world.

00:11:37.650 --> 00:11:40.730
You remember that this was very,
very difficult until

00:11:40.730 --> 00:11:42.360
things like TiVo came along.

00:11:42.360 --> 00:11:45.250
And what they were doing was
leveraging the information

00:11:45.250 --> 00:11:48.730
that was on the internet or
in the community to help--

00:11:48.730 --> 00:11:52.540
instead of saying, I want to
program this amount of time,

00:11:52.540 --> 00:11:54.710
you could say, yeah, I want
to watch this show.

00:11:54.710 --> 00:11:55.440
RETO MEIER: Yeah, which
is always what

00:11:55.440 --> 00:11:56.150
you want to do, right?

00:11:56.150 --> 00:11:58.190
No one just randomly wants
to record half an hour of

00:11:58.190 --> 00:11:59.980
television sometime
on Friday night.

00:11:59.980 --> 00:12:00.720
There is a thing.

00:12:00.720 --> 00:12:02.920
There is something on that
they want to record.

00:12:02.920 --> 00:12:03.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: Usually, yeah.

00:12:03.740 --> 00:12:04.580
RETO MEIER: Generally.

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:08.590
IAN NI-LEWIS: So it turns out
the best way to solve this is

00:12:08.590 --> 00:12:11.300
to have a community repository
so I can go to the internet

00:12:11.300 --> 00:12:14.760
and say, oh yeah, someone else
had a problem where they don't

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:18.180
want to receive alarm
notifications between 10:00 PM

00:12:18.180 --> 00:12:19.890
and 6:00 AM.

00:12:19.890 --> 00:12:23.340
And yet they still want their
clock to be able to

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:24.700
send them an alarm.

00:12:24.700 --> 00:12:28.910
And I pull down that code and
install it into the task

00:12:28.910 --> 00:12:30.460
application that I'm using.

00:12:30.460 --> 00:12:32.060
And boom, I got what I wanted.

00:12:32.060 --> 00:12:34.050
And I didn't have to learn
how to program the thing.

00:12:34.050 --> 00:12:41.080
So the ease of use is important,
but you can get

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:44.610
away with less ease of use if
you have a better repository

00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:47.815
of community scripts that people
can very easily browse

00:12:47.815 --> 00:12:48.860
and install.

00:12:48.860 --> 00:12:49.340
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:12:49.340 --> 00:12:51.750
And this gets to one of the
points which we tend to make

00:12:51.750 --> 00:12:53.890
again and agains-- it's one of
these recurring themes--

00:12:53.890 --> 00:12:56.510
is you want to make it really
easy for people to see the

00:12:56.510 --> 00:12:58.990
value of your app within
the first 30 seconds of

00:12:58.990 --> 00:13:00.220
installing your app.

00:13:00.220 --> 00:13:02.730
So if they can press a couple of
buttons as soon as the app

00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:04.040
is open and say, ah.

00:13:04.040 --> 00:13:05.120
Oh, OK, cool.

00:13:05.120 --> 00:13:09.985
So this is now going to mute my
volume after 9 o'clock at

00:13:09.985 --> 00:13:13.444
night, before 6:00 in the
morning and maximize my alarm.

00:13:13.444 --> 00:13:14.290
That's perfect.

00:13:14.290 --> 00:13:15.330
That's going to be
useful for me.

00:13:15.330 --> 00:13:16.780
I can use this right away.

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:18.740
And it gets their minds thinking
as to how else

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:19.460
they're going to use it.

00:13:19.460 --> 00:13:22.540
If all you're presenting them
with is a blank canvas, hit

00:13:22.540 --> 00:13:26.190
plus to create a new action
and then you've got this

00:13:26.190 --> 00:13:29.310
massive array of controls for
virtually everything, if the

00:13:29.310 --> 00:13:31.000
app is doing the right
thing, it's daunting.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:35.010
It's like, I don't know how I
would even want to use this.

00:13:35.010 --> 00:13:35.730
And they'll move on.

00:13:35.730 --> 00:13:39.620
So make that initial action
of learning the app and

00:13:39.620 --> 00:13:41.805
understanding how to use it as
simple and easy as possible,

00:13:41.805 --> 00:13:42.980
and you'll get a lot of
mileage out of that.

00:13:42.980 --> 00:13:47.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: So let's take a
trip to the top of the power

00:13:47.810 --> 00:13:50.110
curve and possibly the
bottom of the ease of

00:13:50.110 --> 00:13:52.702
use curve with Tasker.

00:13:52.702 --> 00:13:53.040
OK.

00:13:53.040 --> 00:13:55.340
As you know, a feature graphic
is a great way to grab

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:58.210
people's attention and let them
know in a nutshell what

00:13:58.210 --> 00:13:59.270
your app is about.

00:13:59.270 --> 00:14:01.505
And Tasker doesn't have
a feature graphic--

00:14:01.505 --> 00:14:02.340
RETO MEIER: No it doesn't.

00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:02.920
That's unfortunate.

00:14:02.920 --> 00:14:04.590
IAN NI-LEWIS: Which
is very sad.

00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:07.260
So I've gone ahead and tried
to take the liberty of

00:14:07.260 --> 00:14:09.590
creating a quick mock up.

00:14:09.590 --> 00:14:12.710
I'm not an artist, and so this
doesn't have the flair of,

00:14:12.710 --> 00:14:15.240
let's say, a Roman
Nurik design.

00:14:15.240 --> 00:14:18.850
But I think it captures almost
perfectly what the average

00:14:18.850 --> 00:14:22.794
user can expect when
they start Tasker.

00:14:22.794 --> 00:14:23.232
Yeah.

00:14:23.232 --> 00:14:23.670
You like that?

00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:25.460
RETO MEIER: That's
pretty good.

00:14:25.460 --> 00:14:28.330
It's got glow, it's got big
text, which you like.

00:14:28.330 --> 00:14:30.020
Yeah, I think it's
representative.

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:30.700
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:32.130
And a beautiful photo.

00:14:32.130 --> 00:14:32.690
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:14:32.690 --> 00:14:34.290
IAN NI-LEWIS: Only 14 iStock
photo credits.

00:14:34.290 --> 00:14:36.000
RETO MEIER: Nice.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.000
IAN NI-LEWIS: The point that
I'm trying to make--

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:38.550
I'm being a little
[INAUDIBLE].

00:14:38.550 --> 00:14:40.870
It's just like an airliner.

00:14:40.870 --> 00:14:43.210
It might be the best way to get
you where you want to go,

00:14:43.210 --> 00:14:45.990
but there's a good chance that
you're not actually qualified

00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:47.720
to take the wheel and
fly it yourself.

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:49.900
And I think that's the way most
people are going to feel

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:50.730
about Tasker.

00:14:50.730 --> 00:14:52.030
RETO MEIER: That's the
thing about Tasker.

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:54.790
It is an app which
does everything--

00:14:54.790 --> 00:14:57.020
literally everything-- but it is
a little like sitting down

00:14:57.020 --> 00:15:00.630
in the console of a 747 the
first time you open it up.

00:15:00.630 --> 00:15:01.200
IAN NI-LEWIS: Bingo.

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:02.670
RETO MEIER: So you spent a
little more time looking at

00:15:02.670 --> 00:15:03.560
this app, didn't you?

00:15:03.560 --> 00:15:04.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh yeah, yeah.

00:15:07.420 --> 00:15:08.700
It's a great app.

00:15:08.700 --> 00:15:09.750
And oh, yeah--

00:15:09.750 --> 00:15:10.390
RETO MEIER: Let's
switch sides.

00:15:10.390 --> 00:15:12.050
IAN NI-LEWIS: Look at that.

00:15:12.050 --> 00:15:12.742
Yeah.

00:15:12.742 --> 00:15:13.730
RETO MEIER: Nice.

00:15:13.730 --> 00:15:15.890
IAN NI-LEWIS: OK.

00:15:15.890 --> 00:15:17.940
All right.

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:20.310
So Tasker is tackling a
really difficult job.

00:15:20.310 --> 00:15:24.760
The mission of the Tasker app is
to let you define what your

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:28.600
phone does in any specific
set of circumstances.

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:32.750
And it wants to let you define
those circumstances as

00:15:32.750 --> 00:15:36.270
precisely as possible and give
you as many things to do in

00:15:36.270 --> 00:15:38.190
those circumstances
as possible.

00:15:38.190 --> 00:15:40.650
So for instance, you might want
to turn off Wi-Fi when

00:15:40.650 --> 00:15:43.340
you leave your house, or turn
off Bluetooth when your

00:15:43.340 --> 00:15:45.990
battery gets low, or
even-- and this is

00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:47.860
something Tasker can do--

00:15:47.860 --> 00:15:50.780
automatically respond to
text messages when

00:15:50.780 --> 00:15:51.460
you're in the car.

00:15:51.460 --> 00:15:53.540
It sends a little text saying,
sorry, I'm driving.

00:15:53.540 --> 00:15:54.800
I can't respond to you.

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:55.870
Which I think is awesome.

00:15:55.870 --> 00:15:56.540
RETO MEIER: That's very nice.

00:15:56.540 --> 00:15:57.790
Yeah.

00:16:00.990 --> 00:16:02.980
IAN NI-LEWIS: I actually
used Tasker for

00:16:02.980 --> 00:16:04.910
several months myself.

00:16:04.910 --> 00:16:08.620
I don't think I'm as big of a
fan of these apps as you are.

00:16:08.620 --> 00:16:09.700
I have no idea why.

00:16:09.700 --> 00:16:12.760
I think it's just because I have
very irregular habits.

00:16:12.760 --> 00:16:14.810
RETO MEIER: I think that's the
key to these apps, is they

00:16:14.810 --> 00:16:17.480
presume that you are going to
want to respond to the same

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:19.520
situations in the same way.

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:19.800
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:21.940
RETO MEIER: At the same
general time.

00:16:21.940 --> 00:16:22.720
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, exactly.

00:16:22.720 --> 00:16:30.030
Whereas I am irregular, lazy,
and sort of odd in my habits.

00:16:30.030 --> 00:16:31.000
RETO MEIER: You're
a free spirit.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:31.760
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right, exactly.

00:16:31.760 --> 00:16:32.840
And you're practically
British.

00:16:32.840 --> 00:16:37.360
So depending on where you're
coming from, you'll have a

00:16:37.360 --> 00:16:38.870
different experience
with this.

00:16:38.870 --> 00:16:43.410
But there was a time in my life
when our dear employer

00:16:43.410 --> 00:16:47.520
decided to turn on alarms for
all calendar invites that came

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:50.710
from our corporate email center,
which meant that we

00:16:50.710 --> 00:16:54.440
got alarms set on all of
our holiday reminders.

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:55.900
You'd get woken up at midnight,

00:16:55.900 --> 00:16:57.050
going, oh, it's midnight.

00:16:57.050 --> 00:16:57.950
It's Christmas Eve.

00:16:57.950 --> 00:17:00.900
Don't forget to sleep
in tomorrow.

00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:01.770
That was a good time.

00:17:01.770 --> 00:17:07.490
So I specifically used Tasker
to just turn off calendar

00:17:07.490 --> 00:17:12.369
notifications between 11:00 PM
and 1:00 AM, and that worked

00:17:12.369 --> 00:17:13.079
out pretty well.

00:17:13.079 --> 00:17:15.410
RETO MEIER: Nice.

00:17:15.410 --> 00:17:18.440
IAN NI-LEWIS: But when you
think about it, Tasker's

00:17:18.440 --> 00:17:21.240
really offering an environment
for programming your phone.

00:17:21.240 --> 00:17:24.579
So it's not surprising that most
of the people that love

00:17:24.579 --> 00:17:28.310
this app are software engineers,
and using it feels

00:17:28.310 --> 00:17:29.970
like software engineering.

00:17:29.970 --> 00:17:33.960
In fact, you can actually write
Android apps in Tasker.

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:36.150
We're not going to cover
that functionality.

00:17:36.150 --> 00:17:38.930
That's for a different time when
we talk about on-device

00:17:38.930 --> 00:17:41.230
IDE's someday.

00:17:41.230 --> 00:17:42.310
RETO MEIER: That would
be a fun one.

00:17:42.310 --> 00:17:45.770
IAN NI-LEWIS: So it's a very
powerful program, and this is

00:17:45.770 --> 00:17:46.900
really the problem.

00:17:46.900 --> 00:17:50.100
With great power comes great
usability issues.

00:17:50.100 --> 00:17:51.920
My complaint with Tasker,
though, is

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:52.960
not that it's difficult.

00:17:52.960 --> 00:17:53.980
I expected that.

00:17:53.980 --> 00:17:57.150
It's that it's more difficult
than it has to be.

00:17:57.150 --> 00:18:00.860
So let's switch to
the giant phone.

00:18:00.860 --> 00:18:02.790
Oh, and we can swap places.

00:18:02.790 --> 00:18:03.480
RETO MEIER: We're going
to swap back.

00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:04.930
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, yeah.

00:18:04.930 --> 00:18:06.120
RETO MEIER: This is getting
a little crazy.

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:06.520
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:10.660
RETO MEIER: You're going to trip
yourself over my cord.

00:18:10.660 --> 00:18:13.230
IAN NI-LEWIS: I said wireless
mics, and everybody said no,

00:18:13.230 --> 00:18:13.760
that's crazy.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:16.290
And I said, I'm buying them
anyway, and then they sucked,

00:18:16.290 --> 00:18:18.000
and everyone went, OK.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:19.870
RETO MEIER: So now after last
week's issue, some people said

00:18:19.870 --> 00:18:21.730
that we shouldn't use
the giant phone.

00:18:21.730 --> 00:18:24.680
They said that it's too much
phone for us to handle, that a

00:18:24.680 --> 00:18:27.970
smaller, more discreet phone
might suit us better.

00:18:27.970 --> 00:18:32.180
To them I say, witness the power
of our fully operational

00:18:32.180 --> 00:18:32.990
giant phone.

00:18:32.990 --> 00:18:36.860
IAN NI-LEWIS: Which I can
handle just fine.

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:37.330
RETO MEIER: OK.

00:18:37.330 --> 00:18:38.070
Well, that's disturbing.

00:18:38.070 --> 00:18:40.032
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yes.

00:18:40.032 --> 00:18:44.180
So leaving aside the issues that
we have with navigation,

00:18:44.180 --> 00:18:48.530
legacy buttons, and just
general Android design

00:18:48.530 --> 00:18:53.420
guideline issues, let's just
focus on the meat of Tasker.

00:18:53.420 --> 00:18:55.700
Let's actually define a task.

00:18:55.700 --> 00:19:01.890
So when I start up, the first
thing I see is three tabs, is

00:19:01.890 --> 00:19:05.160
Profiles, Tasks, and Scenes.

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:09.170
Now as a user, I'm thinking
to myself, OK, I know

00:19:09.170 --> 00:19:10.360
I want to do tasks.

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:11.820
At least that's what
I thought.

00:19:11.820 --> 00:19:12.250
Right?

00:19:12.250 --> 00:19:12.510
RETO MEIER: Sure.

00:19:12.510 --> 00:19:12.780
It's Tasker, right?

00:19:12.780 --> 00:19:15.280
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now I think that
other people might say, oh, I

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:16.720
want to define a
profile, right?

00:19:16.720 --> 00:19:18.090
It depends on how
you look at it.

00:19:18.090 --> 00:19:18.530
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:19:18.530 --> 00:19:20.350
I think it depends on how
familiar you are with the

00:19:20.350 --> 00:19:23.736
programs and the terminology
that goes around it, because

00:19:23.736 --> 00:19:25.600
it's not always obvious
to me what's a task

00:19:25.600 --> 00:19:27.030
and what's a profile.

00:19:27.030 --> 00:19:27.930
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:19:27.930 --> 00:19:34.770
Now it turns out in Tasker, a
profile is a set of contexts

00:19:34.770 --> 00:19:36.540
that contain tasks.

00:19:36.540 --> 00:19:36.950
RETO MEIER: OK.

00:19:36.950 --> 00:19:37.610
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now you'll
notice there

00:19:37.610 --> 00:19:39.900
is no Context button.

00:19:39.900 --> 00:19:43.090
Instead, there is a Scenes
button, which actually sounded

00:19:43.090 --> 00:19:43.990
like a content.

00:19:43.990 --> 00:19:47.850
Like oh, maybe if I'm in this
scene-- perhaps I have become

00:19:47.850 --> 00:19:49.110
an actor in the scene.

00:19:49.110 --> 00:19:51.990
When I exit stage left.

00:19:51.990 --> 00:19:54.780
RETO MEIER: Are we all not
actors on the stage of life?

00:19:54.780 --> 00:19:57.500
IAN NI-LEWIS: I will be
pursued by a bear.

00:19:57.500 --> 00:19:59.390
So, acting.

00:20:02.230 --> 00:20:03.770
So I immediately went to Scenes

00:20:03.770 --> 00:20:05.440
because that made sense.

00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:08.310
Now it gives me a helpful pop
up, which essentially says,

00:20:08.310 --> 00:20:11.210
please do not press
this button again.

00:20:11.210 --> 00:20:12.430
RETO MEIER: Wait, why did
you press the button?

00:20:12.430 --> 00:20:13.070
Stop pressing it.

00:20:13.070 --> 00:20:13.550
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yes.

00:20:13.550 --> 00:20:17.690
But it turns out that Scenes are
actually the GUI designer

00:20:17.690 --> 00:20:20.860
for writing your own
applications in the Tasker

00:20:20.860 --> 00:20:21.790
design language.

00:20:21.790 --> 00:20:22.880
RETO MEIER: That's
kind of cool.

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:23.480
IAN NI-LEWIS: It is cool.

00:20:23.480 --> 00:20:24.660
RETO MEIER: While you've got
that up as well, what I wanted

00:20:24.660 --> 00:20:27.495
to point out, A, modal
dialog-- please

00:20:27.495 --> 00:20:28.455
don't do modal dialogs.

00:20:28.455 --> 00:20:28.770
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:20:28.770 --> 00:20:30.900
RETO MEIER: Particularly when
it's a modal dialogue popping

00:20:30.900 --> 00:20:32.460
up over an empty screen.

00:20:32.460 --> 00:20:34.390
So I mean, there is
nothing here.

00:20:34.390 --> 00:20:36.750
So if you want to display some
information, that's the

00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:37.500
place to put it.

00:20:37.500 --> 00:20:38.270
Not on a pop-up box.

00:20:38.270 --> 00:20:40.520
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, and that's
really the issue that we're

00:20:40.520 --> 00:20:43.140
going to see over and over again
is that this is a very

00:20:43.140 --> 00:20:45.340
modal dialog based
application.

00:20:45.340 --> 00:20:48.620
And I think part of it,
especially when you look at

00:20:48.620 --> 00:20:50.730
the buttons, I think you can see
that this was definitely

00:20:50.730 --> 00:20:55.185
designed in the Eclair era.

00:20:55.185 --> 00:20:58.110
And that used to be, I think,
a better way of doing things

00:20:58.110 --> 00:20:58.580
than it is now.

00:20:58.580 --> 00:21:00.440
I think we have much
better design

00:21:00.440 --> 00:21:02.610
language now than we did.

00:21:02.610 --> 00:21:04.000
RETO MEIER: I think the problem
was at that time, it

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:04.830
was quite ambiguous.

00:21:04.830 --> 00:21:06.180
And it was really up to you.

00:21:06.180 --> 00:21:08.630
And if you wanted your app to
look good, you really needed

00:21:08.630 --> 00:21:09.510
to do it all yourself.

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:11.680
And I can see that they've put
some effort in here to try and

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:13.070
make it look better
than the stock

00:21:13.070 --> 00:21:15.240
Gingerbread, Eclair stuff.

00:21:15.240 --> 00:21:17.110
Unfortunately, now it starts
to look a little dated.

00:21:17.110 --> 00:21:18.150
And look, I understand.

00:21:18.150 --> 00:21:22.290
We all definitely understand why
people have been reluctant

00:21:22.290 --> 00:21:24.840
to update their app with every
single version of Android.

00:21:24.840 --> 00:21:27.870
But since Holo, since Android
3, things have been pretty

00:21:27.870 --> 00:21:28.480
consistent.

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:29.890
We've added new things.

00:21:29.890 --> 00:21:33.300
But if you create an app which
is consistent with those

00:21:33.300 --> 00:21:35.790
design guidelines, I think
you'll find something which is

00:21:35.790 --> 00:21:36.870
going to look good for
a while to come.

00:21:36.870 --> 00:21:38.660
IAN NI-LEWIS: So I'm really
excited to see what Roman has

00:21:38.660 --> 00:21:39.550
to say about this.

00:21:39.550 --> 00:21:43.940
But I will point out that there
are some great apps on

00:21:43.940 --> 00:21:47.170
Google Play right now that
sign a little bit

00:21:47.170 --> 00:21:47.930
more in this area.

00:21:47.930 --> 00:21:51.130
Now I haven't found anything
with the power of Tasker.

00:21:51.130 --> 00:21:59.680
But for instance, there's an app
called Automate It, which

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:03.660
uses almost an identical
paradigm, but it allows me to

00:22:03.660 --> 00:22:08.620
swipe between the
different pages.

00:22:08.620 --> 00:22:16.170
And as I do different actions,
where Tasker uses modal

00:22:16.170 --> 00:22:23.010
dialogs, Automate It uses drop
downs, and it uses--

00:22:23.010 --> 00:22:25.700
what do we call those things
where they open up?

00:22:25.700 --> 00:22:26.660
RETO MEIER: Like an expanding
list view?

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:27.770
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:22:27.770 --> 00:22:28.540
Exactly.

00:22:28.540 --> 00:22:30.560
So they use expansions.

00:22:30.560 --> 00:22:33.530
One really obvious place, for
instance, is when you choose a

00:22:33.530 --> 00:22:38.100
location on Automate It, then it
expands a map view directly

00:22:38.100 --> 00:22:41.520
underneath the piece of script
that you're working on.

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:43.560
Whereas here, it actually takes
you to a completely

00:22:43.560 --> 00:22:44.120
different screen.

00:22:44.120 --> 00:22:44.450
RETO MEIER: All right.

00:22:44.450 --> 00:22:45.920
So it's just providing you
the context without

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:47.150
breaking your workflow.

00:22:47.150 --> 00:22:47.470
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:22:47.470 --> 00:22:47.790
RETO MEIER: I like that.

00:22:47.790 --> 00:22:50.550
IAN NI-LEWIS: Again, not
a huge big deal.

00:22:50.550 --> 00:22:53.660
Just some things that could
be polished there.

00:22:53.660 --> 00:22:56.670
The important thing is helping
people to understand how these

00:22:56.670 --> 00:22:57.990
things actually work.

00:22:57.990 --> 00:23:01.700
Now these little modal dialogs
that pop up are certainly

00:23:01.700 --> 00:23:06.200
better than nothing, but
could be better.

00:23:06.200 --> 00:23:09.305
Now it is pretty obvious,
though, what I need to do to

00:23:09.305 --> 00:23:10.500
add a profile.

00:23:10.500 --> 00:23:12.900
I don't really want to click
the Plus button down here.

00:23:12.900 --> 00:23:14.600
I probably would've rather
had it in the list,

