00:41:59.150 --> 00:42:02.110
One thing that I really did want
to point out is they have

00:42:02.110 --> 00:42:03.870
a really nice toast.

00:42:03.870 --> 00:42:06.480
So because it's all sort of
automated, [? plus ?] a

00:42:06.480 --> 00:42:09.610
widget, you don't have an
activity to show information,

00:42:09.610 --> 00:42:11.260
you need to use something
like a toast.

00:42:11.260 --> 00:42:13.060
And they've customized their
toasts really well.

00:42:13.060 --> 00:42:14.640
They've added color,
a background.

00:42:14.640 --> 00:42:17.260
So it's not just sort of that
general, standard generic

00:42:17.260 --> 00:42:18.600
toast which pops up.

00:42:18.600 --> 00:42:20.250
IAN NI-LEWIS: And this is one
of the few places where a

00:42:20.250 --> 00:42:21.580
toast is truly appropriate.

00:42:21.580 --> 00:42:22.150
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:42:22.150 --> 00:42:24.660
And it's nice to see that they
have used it appropriately and

00:42:24.660 --> 00:42:27.020
prettied it up as well,
which is great.

00:42:27.020 --> 00:42:29.230
So let's jump to the giant
phone really quickly.

00:42:29.230 --> 00:42:33.760
So if we have a look at Profile
Widget here, you can

00:42:33.760 --> 00:42:37.600
see straight away if we go
back to the main page.

00:42:37.600 --> 00:42:40.720
So the way it works is, you go
into your profiles, and then

00:42:40.720 --> 00:42:43.245
there's Activate Profiles
and Create and Edit.

00:42:43.245 --> 00:42:45.590
And what you actually want to
do for most cases is either

00:42:45.590 --> 00:42:47.400
Create or Edit a profile.

00:42:47.400 --> 00:42:50.490
Reordering and activating
are secondary functions.

00:42:50.490 --> 00:42:53.310
If we go into Editing,
Day, then we end

00:42:53.310 --> 00:42:53.970
up with this screen.

00:42:53.970 --> 00:42:56.730
So we're already having to
navigate deeply into the

00:42:56.730 --> 00:42:57.380
innards of the app.

00:42:57.380 --> 00:43:01.140
And at this point we can do
things like change the icons,

00:43:01.140 --> 00:43:04.740
modify the sound, connection
and screen.

00:43:04.740 --> 00:43:07.480
So one of the others, I guess,
not necessarily issues but

00:43:07.480 --> 00:43:11.020
observations about this app is
it doesn't have quite the same

00:43:11.020 --> 00:43:12.820
level of control that
the others do.

00:43:12.820 --> 00:43:13.690
So you can't do things.

00:43:13.690 --> 00:43:16.310
You can turn on and off Wi-Fi,
but you can't specify a Wi-Fi

00:43:16.310 --> 00:43:18.630
network to connect
to, for example.

00:43:18.630 --> 00:43:20.490
So it's a little bit
more limited in its

00:43:20.490 --> 00:43:22.240
functionality there.

00:43:22.240 --> 00:43:24.730
As well, once you actually have
it set up, it creates

00:43:24.730 --> 00:43:28.970
this really nice widget on the
home screen, which is great.

00:43:28.970 --> 00:43:31.060
Again, they've put a lot of time
into the design effort of

00:43:31.060 --> 00:43:32.540
making sure that the
things you actually

00:43:32.540 --> 00:43:34.100
use a lot look nice.

00:43:34.100 --> 00:43:37.630
And so if I click on the widget,
it lets me choose a

00:43:37.630 --> 00:43:39.290
profile to activate.

00:43:39.290 --> 00:43:41.930
Displays it in the nice little
toast, and then changes the

00:43:41.930 --> 00:43:44.240
actual widget so it can see
what profile you're in.

00:43:44.240 --> 00:43:47.450
So the expectation here is
really much more sort of that

00:43:47.450 --> 00:43:51.415
older approach of defining a
profile for your phone, where

00:43:51.415 --> 00:43:54.170
you basically want to say
night mode, day mode.

00:43:54.170 --> 00:43:56.560
at-home mode, Wi-Fi on
mode, whatever it is.

00:43:56.560 --> 00:43:59.200
IAN NI-LEWIS: I think people
certainly get used to that.

00:43:59.200 --> 00:44:01.240
I mean, we've got airplane mode
for instance, night and

00:44:01.240 --> 00:44:03.670
day mode, work mode,
home mode.

00:44:03.670 --> 00:44:05.300
Those all makes sense,
and I like that.

00:44:05.300 --> 00:44:08.500
It's probably worth mentioning
that Tasker, for instance, and

00:44:08.500 --> 00:44:11.960
most of the other profile apps,
also offer widgets.

00:44:11.960 --> 00:44:12.250
RETO MEIER: Yes.

00:44:12.250 --> 00:44:13.380
IAN NI-LEWIS: If that's
what you're into.

00:44:13.380 --> 00:44:17.830
It's just that they focus most
of their efforts on the more

00:44:17.830 --> 00:44:19.550
interesting conditional stuff.

00:44:19.550 --> 00:44:20.060
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:44:20.060 --> 00:44:22.880
And so I think there is a niche
for an app like this,

00:44:22.880 --> 00:44:26.930
which provides a much smaller,
simpler subset for the most

00:44:26.930 --> 00:44:29.650
common, the 80% of things
which people want to do.

00:44:29.650 --> 00:44:31.860
Turn up screen brightness, mute

00:44:31.860 --> 00:44:33.080
volume, change ring tones.

00:44:33.080 --> 00:44:35.950
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, if I was
trying to do this for my mom,

00:44:35.950 --> 00:44:39.300
this is exactly what I would
use, because I don't want to

00:44:39.300 --> 00:44:42.310
have to do tech support for
the set of profiles and

00:44:42.310 --> 00:44:44.225
conditions that I wrote
to figure out if

00:44:44.225 --> 00:44:45.050
she's at work or not.

00:44:45.050 --> 00:44:45.590
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:44:45.590 --> 00:44:48.330
IAN NI-LEWIS: If she has a
problem with that, I'd rather

00:44:48.330 --> 00:44:50.260
that she just presses
a button.

00:44:50.260 --> 00:44:53.690
Because the code that I can
write in their script is not

00:44:53.690 --> 00:44:56.580
going to be nearly accurate
enough to cover all the cases.

00:44:56.580 --> 00:44:58.950
And if it ever fails,
she's not going to

00:44:58.950 --> 00:44:59.980
be able to fix it.

00:44:59.980 --> 00:45:00.550
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:45:00.550 --> 00:45:02.090
So this is kind of nice.

00:45:02.090 --> 00:45:06.240
So the downside here for this
app is that it's simpler once

00:45:06.240 --> 00:45:08.560
you understand how to use it,
but that learning curve to

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:11.280
understand how you're setting
up your profiles, where that

00:45:11.280 --> 00:45:12.700
happens, how you
place a widget.

00:45:12.700 --> 00:45:15.390
The actual process of putting
your widget on the home screen

00:45:15.390 --> 00:45:18.680
and choosing how it's going to
choose between the different

00:45:18.680 --> 00:45:21.920
profiles you've set up is a
little bit harder and less

00:45:21.920 --> 00:45:22.940
intuitive than it should be.

00:45:22.940 --> 00:45:25.250
So that's, I think, the key for
these guys is to really

00:45:25.250 --> 00:45:29.090
try to make that process as
simple and easy to do.

00:45:29.090 --> 00:45:30.650
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well, I think we
knew this show was going to

00:45:30.650 --> 00:45:33.440
run long, because these
are such complex apps.

00:45:33.440 --> 00:45:37.660
But let's go ahead and talk a
little bit now, wrap it up,

00:45:37.660 --> 00:45:40.400
and see what all these
apps should be doing.

00:45:40.400 --> 00:45:40.950
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:45:40.950 --> 00:45:44.500
So we introduced this stuff
at the beginning.

00:45:44.500 --> 00:45:45.800
We want it to do as
much as possible.

00:45:45.800 --> 00:45:47.030
We want it to be easy to use.

00:45:47.030 --> 00:45:48.740
We want it to work on tablets.

00:45:48.740 --> 00:45:51.990
And tablets, I guess, is one
which I do want to bring up,

00:45:51.990 --> 00:45:54.650
because I think they've all
been designed for phones.

00:45:54.650 --> 00:45:56.780
Which makes sense, but we
really want to try and

00:45:56.780 --> 00:45:59.430
emphasize how much people should
be thinking about doing

00:45:59.430 --> 00:46:00.070
those things.

00:46:00.070 --> 00:46:02.310
And so step one is really
creating a great responsive

00:46:02.310 --> 00:46:04.810
design so that the app is going
to look good and work

00:46:04.810 --> 00:46:07.590
great on any device that
you happen to be using.

00:46:07.590 --> 00:46:09.140
It doesn't matter what
orientation you're in.

00:46:09.140 --> 00:46:10.570
It doesn't matter whether
it's a tablet,

00:46:10.570 --> 00:46:11.450
whether it's a phone.

00:46:11.450 --> 00:46:15.010
Whatever it is, it should just
adapt and work well.

00:46:15.010 --> 00:46:16.850
And similarly, you want
to create that great

00:46:16.850 --> 00:46:18.350
tablet-specific experience.

00:46:18.350 --> 00:46:22.020
And even if you're not planning
to do anything tablet

00:46:22.020 --> 00:46:23.590
specific, it should
still work.

00:46:23.590 --> 00:46:26.050
You shouldn't have to worry
that, well, actually, on my

00:46:26.050 --> 00:46:27.270
Nexus 7, it doesn't work.

00:46:27.270 --> 00:46:29.740
And I have to mount it
differently in my car or place

00:46:29.740 --> 00:46:31.410
the NFC tag in a different
place.

00:46:31.410 --> 00:46:34.980
And so really, you want to
optimize in all ways.

00:46:34.980 --> 00:46:37.950
And in fact, there can be
opportunities to take it a

00:46:37.950 --> 00:46:38.620
step further.

00:46:38.620 --> 00:46:41.510
Now we can see that the NFC
Task Launcher is providing

00:46:41.510 --> 00:46:42.820
some statistics.

00:46:42.820 --> 00:46:44.950
That sort of stuff works really
well on a tablet where

00:46:44.950 --> 00:46:48.045
you may want to sit down, or
indeed for a Tasker, where

00:46:48.045 --> 00:46:51.020
you're having to create GUIs
and those sorts of things.

00:46:51.020 --> 00:46:52.460
That on my phone, not so much.

00:46:52.460 --> 00:46:55.280
That on a tablet, well, I think
we'd all like to be able

00:46:55.280 --> 00:46:56.280
to write code on a tablet.

00:46:56.280 --> 00:46:57.640
Maybe this is the first step.

00:46:57.640 --> 00:46:58.950
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, giving
yourself a little more space

00:46:58.950 --> 00:47:00.460
is always a good thing.

00:47:00.460 --> 00:47:02.010
Although one thing you should
also remember when you're

00:47:02.010 --> 00:47:04.710
going between tablets and phones
is that most people

00:47:04.710 --> 00:47:05.760
have both devices.

00:47:05.760 --> 00:47:07.860
If they have a tablet, they
almost certainly have a phone.

00:47:07.860 --> 00:47:08.190
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:47:08.190 --> 00:47:10.320
IAN NI-LEWIS: And so being able
to create something on

00:47:10.320 --> 00:47:13.560
one device and use it on another
device, or on all of

00:47:13.560 --> 00:47:16.190
your devices, is also
a feature I would

00:47:16.190 --> 00:47:16.850
really like to see.

00:47:16.850 --> 00:47:17.190
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:47:17.190 --> 00:47:19.390
I guess it's the other side of
that community repository.

00:47:19.390 --> 00:47:20.830
I want my own repository.

00:47:20.830 --> 00:47:21.050
IAN NI-LEWIS: Bingo.

00:47:21.050 --> 00:47:22.820
RETO MEIER: It's like I've
created it, I want to apply

00:47:22.820 --> 00:47:24.750
this to all of my devices.

00:47:24.750 --> 00:47:25.920
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:47:25.920 --> 00:47:26.220
Alright.

00:47:26.220 --> 00:47:27.810
So before we sign off, let's
take a look at our

00:47:27.810 --> 00:47:31.020
prescriptions for reach app to
help them move towards a pure

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:32.440
Android experience.

00:47:32.440 --> 00:47:34.180
Do we put that in
scare quotes?

00:47:34.180 --> 00:47:35.850
RETO MEIER: I think until we
actually launch it, yes.

00:47:35.850 --> 00:47:36.685
IAN NI-LEWIS: No problem.

00:47:36.685 --> 00:47:38.060
RETO MEIER: Once it's launched
then we lose the scare quotes.

00:47:38.060 --> 00:47:38.470
IAN NI-LEWIS: Awesome.

00:47:38.470 --> 00:47:39.820
All right.

00:47:39.820 --> 00:47:45.020
So the prescription
we have for Tasker

00:47:45.020 --> 00:47:46.560
is first a UI makeover.

00:47:46.560 --> 00:47:47.400
I think it needs one.

00:47:47.400 --> 00:47:48.240
It deserves one.

00:47:48.240 --> 00:47:49.925
It's a wonderful program,
and it'd be nice

00:47:49.925 --> 00:47:50.900
if it looked nicer.

00:47:50.900 --> 00:47:52.610
RETO MEIER: Yeah, don't
sell yourself short.

00:47:52.610 --> 00:47:54.615
It's a great app with huge
amounts of functionality.

00:47:54.615 --> 00:47:57.460
It just looks like it's old.

00:47:57.460 --> 00:48:00.290
And give it the Holo makeover.

00:48:00.290 --> 00:48:00.760
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:01.670
And lose the dialogs.

00:48:01.670 --> 00:48:03.350
More than anything else,
this is what makes the

00:48:03.350 --> 00:48:04.870
program hard to use.

00:48:04.870 --> 00:48:08.700
It puts you in a very modal
position, so it's difficult to

00:48:08.700 --> 00:48:10.550
quickly edit things because
you have to jump

00:48:10.550 --> 00:48:11.560
in and out of modes.

00:48:11.560 --> 00:48:13.950
I'd love to see a tablet version
where I could see

00:48:13.950 --> 00:48:16.940
multiple conditions, multiple
contacts, and multiple tasks

00:48:16.940 --> 00:48:19.230
all laid out where I could
tweak each one of them.

00:48:19.230 --> 00:48:21.250
RETO MEIER: Oh, that would
be beautiful, yeah.

00:48:21.250 --> 00:48:22.500
IAN NI-LEWIS: They definitely
need a repository.

00:48:22.500 --> 00:48:26.760
The wiki is awesome, but only
if you're willing to really

00:48:26.760 --> 00:48:27.500
work at something.

00:48:27.500 --> 00:48:30.310
Some of the competitors out
there actually have something

00:48:30.310 --> 00:48:34.700
where the first thing you do
is press a button, or you

00:48:34.700 --> 00:48:35.580
don't even need to
press a button.

00:48:35.580 --> 00:48:39.360
You just see popular tasks, or
popular contexts, or popular

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:41.230
profiles that other people
have defined.

00:48:41.230 --> 00:48:46.000
And it turns out, when I went
looking, that everything that

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:49.080
I wanted to do had already been
defined, and all that I

00:48:49.080 --> 00:48:51.860
needed to do is change the
location or change the time.

00:48:51.860 --> 00:48:52.440
RETO MEIER: A couple
of variables, yeah.

00:48:52.440 --> 00:48:54.480
IAN NI-LEWIS: So let's
get that in.

00:48:54.480 --> 00:48:58.780
I think that if that was in the
app, it would be a winner.

00:48:58.780 --> 00:49:02.315
It would be, hands down, my
favorite profile app.

00:49:02.315 --> 00:49:05.110
But finally, I think that you
could have a little bit more

00:49:05.110 --> 00:49:06.730
appropriate feature discovery.

00:49:06.730 --> 00:49:09.050
Things like variables that are
very important-- like if I

00:49:09.050 --> 00:49:11.400
want to see what speed I'm
going, for instance--

00:49:11.400 --> 00:49:12.445
are very difficult
to discover.

00:49:12.445 --> 00:49:15.850
You have to drill all the
way in to a condition.

00:49:15.850 --> 00:49:18.290
And then sometimes you have to
type in the variable name, but

00:49:18.290 --> 00:49:20.410
sometimes you can select
it from a list.

00:49:20.410 --> 00:49:22.820
And that's very, very odd,
especially since there are

00:49:22.820 --> 00:49:26.490
about 100 different built-in
variables that let you check

00:49:26.490 --> 00:49:27.500
different things
on your phone.

00:49:27.500 --> 00:49:29.290
It's really, really nice.

00:49:29.290 --> 00:49:31.870
But then again, you've got the
Scenes feature, which is an

00:49:31.870 --> 00:49:32.460
app builder.

00:49:32.460 --> 00:49:36.930
It's an IDE, which most of the
users of this particular

00:49:36.930 --> 00:49:39.410
application will probably
not use.

00:49:39.410 --> 00:49:40.960
It's a niche feature.

00:49:40.960 --> 00:49:44.240
And yet it's given a very
prominent position on the very

00:49:44.240 --> 00:49:45.010
first page.

00:49:45.010 --> 00:49:47.830
So it's not about making
things more or less

00:49:47.830 --> 00:49:48.590
discoverable.

00:49:48.590 --> 00:49:52.030
It's making them more
appropriately discoverable.

00:49:52.030 --> 00:49:54.020
RETO MEIER: That makes
a lot of sense.

00:49:54.020 --> 00:49:57.390
For NFC Task Launcher, like I
said, they've actually done a

00:49:57.390 --> 00:49:58.920
lot of things that
I was hoping for.

00:49:58.920 --> 00:50:00.900
I think there is still a little
bit of work to be done

00:50:00.900 --> 00:50:01.630
in navigation.

00:50:01.630 --> 00:50:04.050
And that's maybe something that
you guys can find out

00:50:04.050 --> 00:50:07.180
exactly, if I am a one-off case
or if a lot of people are

00:50:07.180 --> 00:50:08.980
having the same problems,
using analytics.

00:50:08.980 --> 00:50:12.075
Find out how many times people
are accidentally exiting out

00:50:12.075 --> 00:50:13.490
of your app.

00:50:13.490 --> 00:50:16.120
Don't put up an "are you sure
you want to exit" dialog.

00:50:16.120 --> 00:50:17.520
That is not a solution.

00:50:17.520 --> 00:50:19.690
That is just an indication that
your navigation is more

00:50:19.690 --> 00:50:21.600
confusing than it needs to be.

00:50:21.600 --> 00:50:24.240
I'd love to see icons for My
Tags because they look really

00:50:24.240 --> 00:50:26.175
nice on that front page.

00:50:26.175 --> 00:50:27.320
The icons exist.

00:50:27.320 --> 00:50:29.970
I copied a profile which had
an icon associated with it.

00:50:29.970 --> 00:50:32.140
So having those there available
for my own apps

00:50:32.140 --> 00:50:35.550
would be really nice.

00:50:35.550 --> 00:50:37.670
What I've said here is avoid
duplicative actions, because

00:50:37.670 --> 00:50:39.890
when I wrote this, I thought
that Finish and Done did the

00:50:39.890 --> 00:50:40.790
same thing.

00:50:40.790 --> 00:50:42.180
As it turns out, they don't.

00:50:42.180 --> 00:50:45.150
So do check out the way the up
affordances are supposed to

00:50:45.150 --> 00:50:47.140
work, and make sure that that's
consistent with the way

00:50:47.140 --> 00:50:48.560
the platform has
been designed.

00:50:48.560 --> 00:50:52.510
IAN NI-LEWIS: And in general,
try to avoid using verbs as

00:50:52.510 --> 00:50:55.590
app titles, because they will
show up as if they were

00:50:55.590 --> 00:50:57.570
buttons to a lot of people.

00:50:57.570 --> 00:50:58.730
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:50:58.730 --> 00:51:01.630
Even experienced Android users
like myself get confused.

00:51:01.630 --> 00:51:02.960
IAN NI-LEWIS: Indeed.

00:51:02.960 --> 00:51:06.250
RETO MEIER: And also take at
leaf out of Profile Widget.

00:51:06.250 --> 00:51:09.330
They've done a really nice job
customizing their toasts.

00:51:09.330 --> 00:51:10.570
I've seen other apps which
have really rich

00:51:10.570 --> 00:51:11.430
notifications.

00:51:11.430 --> 00:51:15.650
We do use both of those things
in this app to notify you that

00:51:15.650 --> 00:51:16.600
the profile has changed.

00:51:16.600 --> 00:51:19.280
So maybe you spend a little bit
of the awesome design work

00:51:19.280 --> 00:51:20.790
that you've done throughout the
rest of the app just to

00:51:20.790 --> 00:51:22.730
make those final couple
of pieces a

00:51:22.730 --> 00:51:23.740
little bit more polished.

00:51:23.740 --> 00:51:26.960
IAN NI-LEWIS: But remember,
for those of you at home

00:51:26.960 --> 00:51:31.740
watching this do not make toasts
for any other reason.

00:51:31.740 --> 00:51:36.080
Toasts that say, please don't
press that button again, no.

00:51:36.080 --> 00:51:38.210
RETO MEIER: This is a perfect
example of where toasts are

00:51:38.210 --> 00:51:39.700
useful and are appropriate.

00:51:39.700 --> 00:51:40.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:51:40.740 --> 00:51:42.560
Because it's a short
lived notification.

00:51:42.560 --> 00:51:43.920
It's a notification.

